To estimate the role of mutational pressure on shaping CUB in 11 genomes, we compared correlation coefficients between overall nucleotide compositions (A%, T%, G%, C%, GC%) and nucleotide compositions at third codon position of the genes (A3%, T3%, G3%, C3%, GC3%) (Table 3
). Significant correlation was found between them at p < 0.01 or p < 0.05, indicating mutational pressure might play an important role in shaping the codon usage bias. This analysis suggests compositional properties under mutational pressure might have affected the codon usage patterns. However, on correlating ENC with GC contents (GC%, GC1%, GC2%, GC3% and GC12%) (Table 4
), we found, significant correlation of ENC with GC3% in NiV M4 (0.819*), NiV M5 (0.842*), NiV M6 (0.845*) and NiV I (0.909*), indicating higher impact of mutational pressure on these genomes of Nipah virus as compared to other genomes.
